\subsection{Initial exploratory analysis}\label{ssec:exploration}


<<casenuove.marriages.validation, echo=F,message=F, warning=F, fig.cap="Showing the main events in the Republic of Venice over the smoothed chart of marriages per year. Red: Black Plague of 1479; gold: War of the League of Cambrai; green: loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto; brown: war of Candia", fig.height=4>>=
ggplot(marriages_by_year, aes(x=year,y=matrimonies))+geom_line()+
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_segment(x=1479, xend=1479,y=0,yend=80,color="red")+ # Black plague
  geom_segment(x=1510, xend=1510,y=0,yend=80,color="gold")+ # League of Cambrai
  geom_segment(x=1573, xend=1573,y=0,yend=80,color="green")+ # Loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto
  geom_segment(x=1645,xend=1645,y=0,yend=80, color="brown") + # Beginning of the Candia war
  ylim(0,80)+
  theme_minimal()
@

In Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.marriages.validation} we show the smoothed and raw graph of marriages per year along with several important events in the history of the Republic\footnote{A more complete analysis of these events, its influence in the social network and corresponding changes of regime in the Republic of Venice is published in \cite{histories4020012}}. After every event with influence in the demography \cite{lane1973venice}, the number of marriages correspondingly declines: the Black Plague of 1479, for instance, shows a number of matrimonies almost always below the trend line (in blue); this occurs again right after the war of the League of Cambrai, which leads to an extended period with marriages below the trend line. The loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto goes even further, designating a complete change of trend, that is accentuated again by the beginning of the 17th century with the war of Candia which eventually led to the loss of Crete and the Republic entering in a terminal decline phase. This, however, falls already outside the period we are interested in.

The main post-hoc validation is the fact that this dataset has been used repeatedly not only by the authors that published it originally, but also by us in \cite{merelo2023self,merelo2024intra,histories4020012}. In general, it is a very good reflection of the social status of different families in the time of the Republic and how they interacted with each other. In particular, \cite{histories4020012} shows how different measures of the matrimonies network reflect the events in the Republic and the different change points that occurred in them.

However, we need to acknowledge the biases present in this dataset, the main one of which is evident in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.number_of_marriages_per_year}: a temporal bias. The number of marriages per year does not really start to be significant until approximately 1400. What this implies is that whatever conclusion we draw for the initial period covered by the social network will need to take into account that the matrimonies present in the network might not be a sufficient sample of the whole set of matrimonies and thus the social network.

This section provides a first examination of the marriage network and its evolution over the period under study. This analysis rests on the assumption that, unlike patrilineal ties, marriage alliances created strong but comparatively transient connections. In particular, both \citet[p. 82]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} and \citet[p. 143]{raines2013rameau} note that these ties typically lasted for about three generations, roughly spanning the period of co-residence across successive cohorts within the same household. On this basis, and assuming a generational length of approximately 25 years \citep{social:memory}, we analyse the network using a 75-year moving window: at any given time, we include only marital ties formed in the preceding 75 years, in order to capture the “living memory” of past social connections. 

<<casenuove.graphs,echo=F,message=F,fig.cap="Marriage networks from 1350 onward, reconstructed every 50 years using matrimonial ties formed in the preceding 75 years. Gold nodes indicate {case vecchie}, red nodes {case nuove} involved in the conspiracy, and white nodes all other {case nuove};  families with one member elected doge during the corresponding period are represented by squares.", out.width="50%", fig.show="hold">>=
DEPTH_IN_YEARS <- 75

lunghi <- family_labels[ family_labels$Group == "Lunghi", ]$Family
ducali <- family_labels[ family_labels$Ducale == 1,]$Family
quaranta_famiglie <- c(lunghi,ducali)

quaranta_famiglie <- quaranta_famiglie[ !(quaranta_famiglie %in% c("Steno", "Da Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

window_sequence <- seq(from = 1350, to = 1600, by = 50)
assortativity <- data.frame( curti_lunghi = numeric(),
                             ducali = numeric(),
                             in_quaranta = numeric(),
                             distance_curti_lunghi = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_corti = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_lunghi = numeric(),
                             intra_lunghi = numeric(),
                             intra_ducali = numeric(),
                             intra_corti = numeric(),
                             intra_quaranta = numeric(),
                             intra_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             quaranta_e_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             year = integer() )

graph_list <- vector("list",length(window_sequence))
excluded_families_list <- vector("list",length(window_sequence))
list_index <- 1

load("data/doges.years.rda")

for (y in window_sequence ) {

  marriages_window <- noble_marriages %>%
    filter(year <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )
  
  doges <- unique(doges.years[ doges.years$Start >= y & doges.years$Start <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS, ]$Family.doge)
  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")
  
  V(marriage_graph)$Faction <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% lunghi, "Lunghi", "Corti")
  V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_lunghi <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Faction == "Lunghi", 1,2)
  assortativity_curti_lunghi <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_lunghi, directed = FALSE)
  
  V(marriage_graph)$Ducale <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Ducale == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_ducali <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali, directed = FALSE)
  
  V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% quaranta_famiglie, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_quaranta <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta, directed = FALSE)
  
  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight
  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% lunghi, "Lunghi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, "Ducali", "Corti"))
  V(marriage_graph)$color <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Lunghi",
                                    "gold", 
                                    ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group=="Ducali","red","white"))
  
  V(marriage_graph)$shape <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% doges, "square", "circle")
  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])
  excluded_families_list[[list_index]] <- V(marriage_graph)$name[component != 1]

  plot(marriage_graph_main,
        vertex.size = 5,
        vertex.label = NA,
       vertex.color = V(marriage_graph)$color,
        edge.width = E(marriage_graph)$weight,
        layout = layout_with_kk,
        main = paste("Marriage Network from", y, "to", y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS)
  )
  graph_list[[list_index]] <- marriage_graph
  list_index <- list_index+1
}
@

 Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.graphs}, which uses the Kamada-Kawai layout algorithm \cite{kamada1989algorithm} provides an overview of the evolution of the marital social network over the period of interest. It shows the main component of six networks constructed using the 75-year moving window, spaced at 50-year intervals (1350–1425, 1400–1475, etc.). In the graph, gold nodes represent \emph{longhi} families, red nodes \emph{curti} families part of the conspiracy and white nodes other \emph{curti} families. Nodes of \emph{ducali} families, i.e., families that had a doge elected in the period under consideration, are represented as squares. Except for the \Sexpr{ excluded_families_list[[6]][1]} family in the last graph, no families are excluded from the  main connected component of each network and the \emph{ducali} families always part of it. 
% BISOGNEREBBE DIRE PIU' CHIARAMENTE QUALI SONO ESCLUSE. POTREBBE ESSERE LA FAMIGLIA STENO CHE SI `E ESINTA SUBITO DOPO LA MORTE DEL DOGE? %The only apparent exception is Steno: in the 1350–1425 network, the family does not belong to the main connected component, since the Steno lineage had become extinct by the time of of doge Steno's death in 1413.
% 

The figure highlights several important features of the network. First, not every \emph{ducali} family occupies a central position in the network. 
Second, the effects of the \emph{curti} conspiracy are clearly visible: no gold squares appear in the second, third, and fourth graphs, i.e., between 1400 and 1575, since all doges were from  \emph{curti} families. 

An additional pattern that emerges from the graphs is the substantial similarity of network structures across periods, with most families remaining closely interconnected, except in the first and last graphs. In the former case, this pattern is probably due to biases in the dataset, which contains fewer recorded marriages for that period. The latter case, however, may reflect the political transformations of the late period, when the \emph{ducali} phase came to an end and the \emph{longhi} families once again began to monopolize the office of doge.  IO NON LA VEDO TUTTA QUESTA DIFFERENZA SULL'ULTIMO GRAFICO. MA IO NON SONO BRAVA A LEGGERE QUESTI GRAFICI
The last graph, in fact, reflects a period of transition where there are two {\em conspiring} doges of the families Donato and Priuli, three other {\em curti} of the families Valier, Pesaro and Erizzo, and 4 {\em lunghi}: Bembo, Corner, Contarini and Memmo.
QUESTO COMMENTO ERA STATO FATTO SUI GRAFICI PRECEDENTI. I NOMI E NUMERI NON SONO CORRETTI (AD ESEMPIO, DONATO E PRIULI HANNO 3 DOGE PERCHE' DONATO NE HA DUE, I LONGHI NE HANNO 8, CI SONO ANCHE ALTRI NON CITATI TIPO DA MOLIN E SAGREDO. DA CAMBIARE/TAGLIARE),

Another interesting aspect is the lack of clear factionalization. In none of the periods do either the conspiring \emph{curti} or the \emph{lunghi} families form internally cohesive clusters that exclude the rest of the patriciate. Although peripheral positions are almost always occupied by “white” nodes---namely \emph{curti} families not part of the conspiracy—--neither of the two “coloured” factions consistently dominates the most central positions in the network.

 <<casenuove.betweenness, echo=F,fig.cap="Sequence of distribution of betweenness for the marriage social networks. Colors are as in the previous figure, gold indicates a lunghi family, while red corresponds to ducali; oversize points correspond to families that have had a doge during the period.", out.width="50%", fig.show="hold">>=
initial_year <- 1350
for (graph in graph_list) {
  V(graph)$betweenness = betweenness(graph)
  betweenness_df <- data.frame( family= V(graph)$name, betweenness = V(graph)$betweenness, 
                                color=ifelse(V(graph)$color == "white","black",V(graph)$color),
                                size=ifelse(V(graph)$shape == "square",4,2)
  )
  betweenness_df_sorted <- betweenness_df[order(betweenness_df$betweenness, decreasing=T),]
  betweenness_df_sorted <- betweenness_df_sorted[ betweenness_df_sorted$betweenness > 0,]
  betweenness_df_sorted$index <- seq_len(nrow(betweenness_df_sorted))
  print(ggplot( betweenness_df_sorted, aes(x=index,y=betweenness))+
          geom_point(color=betweenness_df_sorted$color,alpha=0.5,
                     size=betweenness_df_sorted$size)+
          scale_x_log10()+scale_y_log10(limits = c(0.1, 1900))+theme_minimal()+xlab(paste("Years", initial_year, "-", initial_year+DEPTH_IN_YEARS)))
  initial_year <- initial_year + 50
#  print(betweenness_df_sorted[1,])
}
@

To better understand the structure of political intermediation within the Venetian patriciate, Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.betweenness} shows the distribution of betweenness centrality by rank across the six overlapping periods.  All graphs share the same $y$-axis scale, while the $x$ axis reports the rank of families with a betweenness value greater than zero. This common scale makes it possible to compare the degree of concentration of intermediation power across periods. The colours follow the same classification used in the previous figure, distinguishing between  \emph{lunghi}, conspiracy \emph{curti}, and other \emph{curti}.  Larger points represent families that elected a doge during the corresponding period.

A first observation is the absence of extreme centralization around a single family. Maximum betweenness values remain around 1000 with a slight decline observable in the 1500--1575 and 1550--1625 graphs. A further notable feature is that, rather than displaying the steep decay typically associated with a power-law distribution, all graphs exhibit a pronounced ``broken-stick'' pattern: a relatively large group of families shares similarly high betweenness values, followed by a sharp decline around the 100th rank. 

This pattern suggests the existence of a broad elite endowed with comparable intermediation power, rather than the dominance of few families. In turn, this supports the well-established interpretation of Venetian political institutions as mechanisms designed to prevent excessive concentration of power. At the same time, the sharp separation between highly central and peripheral families indicates that substantial inequalities persisted within the patriciate, despite the formal political equality of nobles. Peripheral families appear structurally dependent on a more central elite that mediated access to the wider network.

Such a distribution of intermediation power may help explain the pattern of doge selection observed during the period under study.  However, further investigation would be necessary to determine the exact composition, cohesion, and long-term stability of this elite. The colour patterns in the graph provide some preliminary indications in this regard. The forty families, i.e., the  \emph{longhi} and the conspiring \emph{curti} families, rank higher in terms of centrality, whereas lower ranks are predominantly composed of other \emph{curti} families. Nevertheless, no single faction consistently dominates the top positions across all periods. For example, in the third graph (1450--1525), the highest-ranked family does not belong to the forty families, while in the fourth graph all three colors appears among the most central families. Overall, the graphs point less to the stable predominance of a single faction than to a rotation of influence within a restricted elite.

 Turning now to the \emph{ducali} families, represented in the graph by larger points, another important pattern emerges. The family that succeeds in electing a doge is not necessarily the one occupying the most central position in the network. In most periods, \emph{ducali} families are distributed across the ranking, including relatively peripheral positions, and do not systematically coincide with the families displaying the highest betweenness values. Only in the final two periods (1550--1625 and 1600--1675), that is, in the years surrounding the end of the conspiracy in 1612, do the most central families also manage to secure the election of one of their members as doge. Yet even in these periods, the dogeship was not monopolized by the network's central actors, as several doges continued to be drawn from families occupying relatively peripheral positions. The fact that \emph{ducali} families are found throughout the ranking is consistent with an electoral system that required large majorities: winning the dogeship depended on building broad coalitions capable of attracting support from both central and peripheral segments of the patriciate.

From this initial exploratory analysis we can draw several conclusions: first, that the position of doge is {\em rarely} taken by the family with the highest social status. Second there is not a clear division between so-called {\em factions}: all families have ties with each other, and most of them are indeed connected one way or another. We need then to see whether there is another angle of analysis that can explain the monopolization of the doges by the conspiring \emph{curti} during a 200-year period.

\subsection{Searching for factions in social networks}\label{ssec:methods}

PENSO CHE QUESTA PARTE DEBBA ESSERE ANTICIPATA PERCHE' ABBIAMO GIA' USATO QUESTE CLASSIFICAZIONI. SE MI DAI L'OK PROCEDO.

Before doing any further analysis, we should indicate which are the groups that have been known to exist within the Republic of Venice for the period under study. We should emphasize here that we are not so much talking about {\em parties} in the sense that the population is divided along party lines. They rather work as {\em power cores} or elites \citep{LARSEN201755}, defined by some common feature, with the rest of the population at a certain (social) distance. The fact that, in the 75-year period seen above, most families are linked in a single network prevents any family from being really apart from whatever power core we define.

<<casenuove.table.parties, message=F, echo=F>>=
sort_with_empty_last <- function(x) {
  x[order(x == "", x)]
}
quaranta_famiglie <- c(lunghi,ducali)
quaranta_famiglie <- quaranta_famiglie[ !(quaranta_famiglie %in% c("Steno", "Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

chojnacki_50 <- c( quaranta_famiglie, "Barbo", "Belegno", "Da Molin", "Lion", "Mosto", "Barbaro", "Minio", "Bondumier", "Capello", "De Mezzo", "Viaro", "Gabriel", "Foscarini","Rosso", "Pisani", "Nani")
chojnacki_50 <- chojnacki_50[!is.na(chojnacki_50)]

max_length <- length(chojnacki_50)

length(quaranta_famiglie) <- max_length
quaranta_famiglie[ is.na( quaranta_famiglie )] <- ""

length( ducali ) <- max_length
ducali[ is.na( ducali )] <- ""

length( lunghi ) <- max_length
lunghi[ is.na( lunghi ) ] <- ""

family_lists <- data.frame( ducali = sort_with_empty_last(ducali), 
                            lunghi = sort_with_empty_last(lunghi), 
                            quaranta = sort_with_empty_last(quaranta_famiglie), 
                            chojnacki_50 = sort_with_empty_last(chojnacki_50) )

library(kableExtra)
kable(family_lists, 
      col.names=c("Ducali","Lunghi","Quaranta families", "Chojnacki's richest"),
      caption="List of families used in the paper") %>%
  row_spec(0,bold=TRUE) %>% 
  kable_styling(font_size = 7)
@

We have already mentioned part of these power groups. Here is the whole list, also shown in Table \ref{tab:casenuove.table.parties}, along with their defining feature.\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Lunghi}: "old" families, mostly those that became noble, or were considered noble, in the precise moment the concept of noble was being defined in Venice, that is, during the Serrata. 
\item {\bf Ducali}: According to \cite{raines2003cooptazione}, the families that managed to have one of their members elected doge during the period we are studying.
\item {\bf Quaranta} or the "Forty" families. According to \cite{chojnacki97} these were the families that had the most power for an extended period starting with the Serrata. They added 16 of the Raines Ducali families (excluding Steno, Ponte and Cicogna to the {\em lunghi}, resulting in effectively 40 families.
\item {\bf Wealthy families}: during the 14 century a kind of census called {\em estimo} \citep{estimo} was made and published, listing the assets every noble family in Venice had. We have taken the most wealthy among them according to the published lists. This group, that overlaps the others, had in common their accumulation of capital, which in mercantile republics like Venice was correlated with social and political capital.
\end{itemize}

A priori, it is impossible to know in advance which group had the highest cohesion so that it could act as a single entity and push forward a candidate of their own in a complicated electoral environment such as the election of doge in the Republic of Venice. We will do so next.

\section{Experiments and results}

What we are interested in is to check the cohesion of the different possible factions. Since we are speaking about a power core and a periphery, we are mainly speaking about distances in network terms, that is, how easy would be to reach any member of the social network from any other, and how these evolve; in time, a group can gain or lose cohesiveness if distances among them change, and it can also {\em dilute} itself among the rest if it is {\em closer} in network terms to its periphery. Our main hypothesis here would be that the faction that is able to {\em differentiate less} from its periphery while maintaining a high cohesion itself would be more likely to gather a qualified majority big enough to be able to get closer, or even achieve, election to office of dogeship.

In order to measure that, and the evolution with time, we process additionally the network in two ways\begin{itemize}
\item We will create slices in 5 year increments, in order to have a more fine-grained view of the evolution
\item For every 75-year slice, we will extract the main connected component.
\end{itemize}

<<casenuove.cohesiveness.setup, echo=F, fig.height=5, fig.pos="h!tb", fig.cap="Evolution of the number of families in the main connected component; red line woul be the total number (total number of vertices), with black being the number of families (vertices) in the main connected component.">>=
window_sequence <- seq(from = min(noble_marriages$year), to = 1660, by = 5)
distances_window <- data.frame( total = numeric(),
                             ducali = numeric(),
                             ducali_norm = numeric(),
                             non_ducali = numeric(),
                             non_ducali_norm = numeric(),
                             ducali_vs_non = numeric(),
                             ducali_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                             lunghi = numeric(),
                             lunghi_norm = numeric(),
                             non_lunghi = numeric(),
                             non_lunghi_norm = numeric(),
                             lunghi_vs_non = numeric(),
                             lunghi_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                             quaranta = numeric(),
                             quaranta_norm = numeric(),
                             non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             non_quaranta_norm = numeric(),
                             quaranta_vs_non = numeric(),
                             quaranta_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                             chojnacki = numeric(),
                             chojnacki_norm = numeric(),
                             non_chojnacki = numeric(),
                             non_chojnacki_norm = numeric(),
                             chojnacki_vs_non = numeric(),
                             chojnacki_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                             year = integer() )

power_periphery_timeline <- data.frame( ducali = numeric(),
                                        clique_index_ducali = numeric(),
                                        lunghi = numeric(),
                                        clique_index_lunghi = numeric(),
                                        in_quaranta = numeric(),
                                        clique_index_quaranta = numeric(),
                                        chojnacki = numeric(),
                                        clique_index_chojnacki = numeric(),
                                        year = integer() )

number_of_families_timeline <- data.frame( total_number = integer(),
                                           families_in_MCC = integer(),
                                           percentage_in_MCC = numeric(),
                                           year = integer())
for (y in window_sequence ) {

  marriages_window <- noble_marriages %>%
    filter(year <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )
  
  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")
  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight
  
  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% lunghi, "Lunghi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, "Ducali", "Corti"))
  
  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])
  
  number_of_families <- length(V(marriage_graph)$name)
  families_in_MCC <- length(V(marriage_graph_main)$name)
  percentage_in_MCC <- number_of_families / families_in_MCC
                               
  number_of_families_timeline <- rbind( number_of_families_timeline,
                                        data.frame( total_number = number_of_families,
                                                    families_in_MCC = families_in_MCC,
                                                    percentage_in_MCC = percentage_in_MCC,
                                                    year = y))
  
  distance <- distances(marriage_graph_main, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  average_distance <- mean(distance)
  
  vertices_lunghi <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group == "Lunghi"]
  vertices_non_lunghi <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group != "Lunghi"]
  
  distance_lunghi_non_lunghi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_lunghi, to = vertices_non_lunghi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_lunghi_non_lunghi <- mean(distance_lunghi_non_lunghi)
  
  distances_lunghi_lunghi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_lunghi, to = vertices_lunghi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_lunghi_lunghi <- mean(distances_lunghi_lunghi)
  
  distances_non_lunghi_non_lunghi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_lunghi, to = vertices_non_lunghi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_lunghi_non_lunghi <- mean(distances_non_lunghi_non_lunghi)
  
  clique_index_lunghi <- mean_lunghi_non_lunghi - mean_lunghi_lunghi
  power_periphery_lunghi_index <- ( mean_non_lunghi_non_lunghi - mean_lunghi_non_lunghi ) / clique_index_lunghi
                           
  vertices_ducali <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group == "Ducali"]
  vertices_non_ducali <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group != "Ducali"]
  
  distance_ducali_non_ducali <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_ducali, to = vertices_non_ducali, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_ducali_non_ducali <- mean(distance_ducali_non_ducali)
  
  distances_ducali_ducali <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_ducali, to = vertices_ducali, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_ducali_ducali <- mean(distances_ducali_ducali)
  
  distances_non_ducali_non_ducali <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_ducali, to = vertices_non_ducali, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_ducali_non_ducali <- mean(distances_non_ducali_non_ducali)
  
  clique_index_ducali <- mean_ducali_non_ducali - mean_ducali_ducali
  power_periphery_ducali_index <- ( mean_non_ducali_non_ducali - mean_ducali_non_ducali )/clique_index_ducali
  
  vertices_quaranta <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$name %in% quaranta_famiglie]
  vertices_non_quaranta <- V(marriage_graph_main)[!(V(marriage_graph_main)$name %in% quaranta_famiglie)]
  
  distance_quaranta_non_quaranta <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_quaranta, to = vertices_non_quaranta, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_quaranta_non_quaranta <- mean(distance_quaranta_non_quaranta)
  
  distance_quaranta_quaranta <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_quaranta, to = vertices_quaranta, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_quaranta_quaranta <- mean(distance_quaranta_quaranta)
  
  distance_non_quaranta_non_quaranta <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_quaranta, to = vertices_non_quaranta, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_quaranta_non_quaranta <- mean(distance_non_quaranta_non_quaranta)
  
  clique_index_quaranta <- mean_quaranta_non_quaranta - mean_quaranta_quaranta
  power_periphery_quaranta_index <- ( mean_non_quaranta_non_quaranta - mean_quaranta_non_quaranta )/clique_index_quaranta
  
  vertices_chojnacki <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$name %in% chojnacki_50]
  vertices_non_chojnacki <- V(marriage_graph_main)[!(V(marriage_graph_main)$name %in% chojnacki_50)]
  
  distance_chojnacki_non_chojnacki <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_chojnacki, to = vertices_non_chojnacki, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_chojnacki_non_chojnacki <- mean(distance_chojnacki_non_chojnacki)
  
  distance_chojnacki_chojnacki <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_chojnacki, to = vertices_chojnacki, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_chojnacki_chojnacki <- mean(distance_chojnacki_chojnacki)
  
  distance_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_chojnacki, to = vertices_non_chojnacki, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki <- mean(distance_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki)
  
  clique_index_chojnacki <- mean_chojnacki_non_chojnacki - mean_chojnacki_chojnacki
  power_periphery_chojnacki_index <- ( mean_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki - mean_chojnacki_non_chojnacki )/clique_index_chojnacki
  
  distances_window <- rbind(distances_window,
                         data.frame( total = average_distance,
                                     ducali = mean_ducali_ducali,
                                     ducali_norm = mean_ducali_ducali / average_distance,
                                     non_ducali = mean_non_ducali_non_ducali,
                                     non_ducali_norm = mean_non_ducali_non_ducali / average_distance,
                                     ducali_vs_non = mean_ducali_non_ducali,
                                     ducali_vs_non_norm = mean_ducali_non_ducali / average_distance,
                                     lunghi = mean_lunghi_lunghi,
                                     lunghi_norm = mean_lunghi_lunghi / average_distance,
                                     non_lunghi = mean_non_lunghi_non_lunghi,
                                     non_lunghi_norm = mean_non_lunghi_non_lunghi / average_distance,
                                     lunghi_vs_non = mean_lunghi_non_lunghi,
                                     lunghi_vs_non_norm = mean_lunghi_non_lunghi / average_distance,
                                     quaranta = mean_quaranta_quaranta,
                                     quaranta_norm = mean_quaranta_quaranta / average_distance,
                                     non_quaranta = mean_non_quaranta_non_quaranta,
                                     non_quaranta_norm = mean_non_quaranta_non_quaranta / average_distance,
                                     quaranta_vs_non = mean_quaranta_non_quaranta,
                                     quaranta_vs_non_norm = mean_quaranta_non_quaranta / average_distance,
                                     chojnacki = mean_chojnacki_chojnacki,
                                     chojnacki_norm = mean_chojnacki_chojnacki / average_distance,
                                     non_chojnacki = mean_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki,
                                     non_chojnacki_norm = mean_non_chojnacki_non_chojnacki / average_distance,
                                     chojnacki_vs_non = mean_chojnacki_non_chojnacki,
                                     chojnacki_vs_non_norm = mean_chojnacki_non_chojnacki / average_distance,
                                     year = y))
  
  power_periphery_timeline <- rbind(power_periphery_timeline,
                                     data.frame( ducali = power_periphery_ducali_index,
                                                 clique_index_ducali = clique_index_ducali,
                                                 lunghi = power_periphery_lunghi_index,
                                                 clique_index_lunghi = clique_index_lunghi,
                                                 in_quaranta = power_periphery_quaranta_index,
                                                 clique_index_quaranta = clique_index_quaranta,
                                                 chojnacki = power_periphery_chojnacki_index,
                                                 clique_index_chojnacki = clique_index_chojnacki,
                                                 year = y))
}

ggplot( number_of_families_timeline , aes(x=year, y=total_number) ) + geom_line( color="red") +
  geom_line(data=number_of_families_timeline, aes(y=families_in_MCC)) + theme_minimal()
@

As an initial bird's sight-view of the network, we have plotted in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.cohesiveness.setup} the evolution of the network in terms of number of nodes (different families) as well of the number of families that are actually connected in the main connected component. It is remarkable that, most of the time, all families are connected (in the 75 year span of the network slice); there are three periods where this does not happen: the initial period, which is not so well covered by the dataset, a brief period in the last half of the 15th century, and them practically after the battle of Lepanto in the second half of the 16th century. In general we can say, however, that most noble families are actually connected directly or not and that, even as new families are incorporated into the Golden Book, they become connected almost immediately to the rest of the families and, thus, are susceptible to mutual influence by whatever power core is exerting it at any moment.

